<HEADLINE>
FT  19 APR 91 / Jobless tops 2m after biggest ever monthly rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RACHEL JOHNSON and PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNEMPLOYMENT in Britain passed the 2m mark in March with the biggest monthly
increase on record, unleashing fierce criticism of the government a
fortnight ahead of the local elections.
The Department of Employment's announcement that seasonally-adjusted
unemployment rose by 113,000 to 2.1m last month led to heated clashes in the
House of Commons over the government's economic record and renewed
speculation about the timing of the general election.
The record rise pushed up the unemployment rate to 7.4 per cent, from 7 per
cent in February. Unemployment has risen for 12 consecutive months and by
almost half a million since the rise began.
Mr Tony Blair, Labour's employment spokesman, said: 'Mr Major's classless
society is now a jobless society for over 2m unemployed.'
Separate figures deepened the gloom as the government announced the biggest
fall in manufacturing output for three years. Between January and February,
output declined by 1.6 per cent. Officials said the rate of decline was
increasing and there was no sign of the recession reaching a trough.
Opposition parties called for further cuts in interest rates which were
echoed in private by some Conservative MPs. Mr Norman Lamont, the
chancellor, however, told the Commons that cuts would depend on further
falls in the inflation rate.
Figures published yesterday also showed that average earnings across the
whole economy rose 9 1/4 per cent in the year to February - compared with an
annual rise of 9 1/2 per cent to January. Smaller bonuses and a drop in
overtime hours worked had produced the drop, officials said. It would be
hasty to attribute it to an easing in inflationary wage settlements.
Mr Major's close advisers insist that an unexpectedly good result in the May
local elections could yet persuade him to seek a new mandate in June.
However, yesterday's figures, which confirmed that the brunt of the jobless
rise is being felt in Conservative-held seats in south-east England,
reinforced the view of most ministers that the autumn now looks the earliest
possible general election date.
There has been the first substantial rise in service sector unemployment -
concentrated in the south-east - since 1982, with a rise of 82,000 in the
last quarter of 1990.
With any improvement in the employment outlook likely to lag the expected
upturn in the economy later in the year, some senior colleagues believe that
the prime minister would do better to wait until next year before calling an
election.
Labour plans an intensive campaign to taunt Mr Major for his refusal to call
a summer poll, using it to reinforce its charge that the prime minister is a
'ditherer'. Mr Neil Kinnock, the Labour leader, called Mr Major the 'prime
minister of unemployment'.
Mr Michael Howard, the employment secretary, said the UK unemployment rate
was lower than the European Community average of an estimated 8.5 per cent
last month.
As the government was 'clearly winning the battle against inflation,' there
would be a return to employment growth, he said.
For the short-term, however, most economists expect unemployment to rise for
another year. The employment department said the underlying trend - based on
the rate over the three months to March - had risen to 83,500 a month.
On an unadjusted basis, the jobless total increased by 97,000 to 2.1m.
Output decline Page 10R&amp;D falls Page 10 Editorial comment Page 22 Money
Markets Page 39 London Stocks Page 48
