<HEADLINE>
FT  19 APR 91 / Gorbachev fails to settle Kurile islands dispute
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEFAN WAGSTYL and JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE SOVIET UNION and Japan failed last night to reconcile differences dating
from 1945.
Soviet hopes that Mr Mikhail Gorbachev, the Soviet leader, on his first trip
to Japan, might secure a new source of aid for his ailing economy ended in
disappointment in spite of late-night efforts and no fewer than six summit
meetings with Mr Toshiki Kaifu, the Japanese prime minister.
A joint communique, signed with ceremony at midnight, did no more than
commit the two parties to further talks on the territorial dispute over the
four Kurile islands, or Northern Territories, which has plagued relations
since the Second World War.
Despite repeated efforts, Mr Kaifu failed to win any acknowledgment of
Japan's claim to the Soviet-held territory. The main concession was the
Soviets' explicit recognition - for the first time since 1956 - of the
existence of the territorial issue.
The Soviet side also agreed to reduce the number of troops on the islands
(the Japanese had asked for their removal), to allow Japanese visits to the
islands without visas and start mutual economic activities there.
At a press conference early today the Soviet leader said the two sides could
feel more confident about a breakthrough in the future, 'but everything is
ahead of us.'
Mr Gorbachev and Mr Kaifu held six sessions totalling more than 10 hours
devoted to the issue, which Mr Gorbachev later described as the toughest he
had had for some time.
Mr Kaifu, in a press conference, said he hoped that after 45 years of
waiting, talks which would lead to a peace treaty would now be accelerated.
The territorial dispute has blocked the signing of a Second World War peace
treaty.
It became apparent even before the communique that the hope invested in the
meeting had been excessively optimistic. The Soviet desperation for aid and
technological help bred an expectation that a 'sale' of the islands might
yield at least Dollars 20bn. On the Japanese side, hopes were fanned by
politicians who wished to make their mark on history with a settlement.
Domestic constraints on Mr Gorbachev, including military opposition to
concessions, did not allow him to go as far as many thought he might.
The Soviet leader leaves today for a one-day visit to South Korea and talks
with President Roh Tae Woo.
Soviet strikes, Page 2
Editorial Comment, Page 22
</TEXT>
