<HEADLINE>
FT  19 APR 91 / International Company News: Manville in asbestos trust
charge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANVILLE, the Denver-based industrial products group, has begun setting
aside a portion of its profits to settle thousands of claims by victims of
its previous involvement in the asbestos business.
Manville's first-quarter earnings include an Dollars 8.1m 'profit- sharing'
charge earmarked for the Manville Personal Injury Settlement Trust, one of
two agencies formed to handle the asbestos poisoning claims.
One of the conditions for Manville's emergence from Chapter 11 bankruptcy in
1988 was a commitment to set aside 20 per cent of earnings for the personal
injury trust. The payments will begin in 1992, but are based on the previous
year's earnings. The other trust deals with property damage claims.
Despite the profit - sharing charge, Manville, whose business is now centred
on paper and packaging products, building materials, industrial fibre glass
and minerals, lifted net income to Dollars 35m, or 26 cents a share, in the
first quarter, from Dollars 24.9m, or 18 cents, a year earlier.
The improvement was entirely due, however, to receipt of about Dollars 40m
in settlement of a patent infringement lawsuit. Net sales slipped to Dollars
495.7m from Dollars 518m, and operating income was down to Dollars 41.6m
from Dollars 65.5m. The building products business was especially hard hit.
The Manville personal injury trust was set up in 1988 with about Dollars
2.5bn in assets. However it ran out of cash early last year after settling
claims more quickly than expected and finding itself deluged with
applications for relief from about 170,000 victims.
The trust's immediate problems were relieved in November with a refinancing
agreement involving the trust converting Manville preferred shares into
common stock, thereby entitling it to special dividends.
A new compensation system means that the most seriously ill asbestos victims
now have priority in the settlement of their claims. A ceiling has also been
placed on fees for claimants' lawyers.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
