<HEADLINE>
FT  19 APR 91 / The Lex Column: The rising cost of inflation
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
FT-SE Index: 2,538.4 (-6.6)
In the usual heartless way of the markets, yesterday's headline figure of 2m
unemployed in the UK might have been received as good news. But the market
is also a political animal. Not only is a perilous figure of 2.5m now on the
cards by the year end; an unnerving 43 per cent of the last month's new
jobless also came in the Tory territories of London and the south-east.
Taken with yesterday's reported sharp drop in industrial output, the figures
are suggesting that the recession is worse than imagined. About the only
bright spot was the 9 1/4 per cent rise in average earnings, the lowest
figure for more than a year. At the same time, the 12.1 per cent rise in
unit labour costs was a sharp reminder of how slow inflationary pressures
are to respond to economic downturn. There can be little doubt that the
mechanism will work eventually; with unemployment rising at an average of
about 100,000 a month and headline inflation plunging, wage inflation ought
to be coming down sharply in the near future. The worry is rather the degree
of pain it takes to achieve the desired effect. It is scarcely a good omen
for the behaviour of the UK economy under the still untested disciplines of
the ERM.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
