<HEADLINE>
FT  19 APR 91 / Parliament and Politics: Government 2-1 defeat over murder
sentences - Criminal justice
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE POLICY of mandatory life sentences for murder was shattered by the Lords
yesterday as peers rejected government advice and decided to give judges
discretion to impose whatever sentences they thought fit.
Senior judges led the cross-bench revolt which defeated the government by
more than two-to-one in the committee discussion of the Criminal Justice
Bill.
Peers voted by 177 to 79, a majority of 98 against the government, to follow
the advice of a Lords select committee on murder, and give judges the option
of sentencing murderers to set prison terms.
They then defeated the government again - by 120 votes to 68 - in deciding
that where life imprisonment was imposed, the judge would be required to
give his reasons and indicate how many years should be served.
The government intends to overturn the Lords' decisions when the bill
returns to the Commons, but the scale of the defeats must raise doubts about
whether it will be able to insist on returning to the previous position.
Lord Lane, the lord chief justice, said judges could set the appropriate
sentence for murder as for other serious crimes, and that the trial judge
was in the best position to determine the right penalty.
Lord Nathan, who had chaired the select committee, said the sentence should
be a decision in open court, rather than taken in secrecy by the home
secretary as it is under the present system. The range of crimes within the
definition of murder, he said, was so wide that imposing a life sentence in
all of them diluted its gravity and credibility.
Lord Waddington, the leader of the Lords and a former home secretary, said
the government had concluded that the proposed change would damage public
confidence in the criminal justice system and in the judiciary.
</TEXT>
