<DATE>910418
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  18 APR 91 / London Stock Exchange: Volatile trading in NatWest
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE performance of NatWest Bank confounded the market. The stock eased back
for much of the session, then dipped sharply after bad news from its US
subsidiary, before staging an about-turn late in the session.
Dealers took a bearish tack at the outset, marking the stock down to around
327p, amid worries that first quarter figures from NatWest Bancorp, the US
arm, would be below the Dollars 75m-Dollars 150m loss range forecast by City
analysts. Also acting as a drag was a bearish appraisal of the banking
sector, especially NatWest, published by the bank's own securities arm,
County NatWest.
County said the sector was 10-15 per cent overvalued. It seemed unlikely
that the UK banks would be able to fund their own requirements and that
deterioration in balance-sheet ratios might prompt fears of rights issues,
which would in turn damage share performance
First-quarter figures from Bancorp came out at a loss of Dollars 191m and
when NatWest shares dropped to 323p, heavy buying from institutions reversed
the trend and left the stock a net 4 higher at 335p. Turnover reached 3.4m.
Dilution worries
Short-term factors continued to unsettle Smiths Industries, the first being
renewed concern about the extra research and development costs involved in
the Dollars 700m contract awarded last week by Boeing. The development of
new systems for the US manufacturer's B777 aircraft could amount to Pounds
10m a year, say analysts, and may hold back profits in the next three years
until revenue flow begins.
Another worry was the prospect of further short-term dilution if the group
used its cash pile of some Pounds 120m on an acquisition. The group tends to
follow a policy of longer-term expansion and, in the near term, profit
margins could come under pressure. The shares moved against the market,
falling to 270p before ending 4 down on balance at 272p.
Glaxo recommended
Glaxo led pharmaceuticals higher as Kleinwort Benson said the shares were
oversold, while a presentation in the health and household sector at S. G.
Warburg attracted attention to the whole sector.
The shares have been hit in recent days by the prospect of a law suit
challenging one of the patents on Glaxo's Zantac, the world's best-selling
drug. Mr Ian White at Kleinwort said this presented a short-term buying
opportunity and the shares rose 15 to 1100p.
Glaxo had also been affected by switching from SmithKline Beecham, which
continued to benefit from presentations to analysts on Monday in London and
on Friday in New York. Traders said there was still an overhang of buying
from the US encouraged by the recently strong dollar. In a shortage of
stock, SmithKline was squeezed 13 to 831p.
The good sentiment spilt over into Fisons, 11 1/2 better at 481p, and
Reckitt and Colman, which closed 32 to the good at 1547p as traders spoke of
a shortage of stock.
Kleinwort Benson was involved in the oil sector, re-affirming their strong
buy stance on British Gas and also issuing a detailed buy note on Ultramar.
Kleinwort said British Gas shares already discounted even the most severe
adjustment to the gas pricing formula from the industry watchdog, Ofgas.
'Unless it's a real hammer blow the shares will go up,' said Mr Philip
Lambert at Kleinwort. Gas settled 5 1/2 firmer at 357p on 5.7m. Ultramar
added 7 at 330p.
Racal Telecom advanced strongly, boosted primarily by a buy note from UBS
Philips &amp; Drew, but also by revived speculation that a bid could be imminent
for Racal Electronics before the latter's demerger of Telecom, expected this
summer.
Talk of a bid from Cable &amp; Wireless, on its own or in conjunction with
Mannesman and Hutchison Whampoa, has been in the market for some time. UBS
said Racal Telecom was its only buy recommendation in UK telecoms,
describing it as the premier play on long term growth in mobile telecoms.
Telecom closed 12 up at 393p and Electronics 8 1/2 higher at 241 1/2 p.
GEC, restrained by yet more profits downgrades - Smith New Court was the
latest - could only manage a 3 gain to 205p. Booker rose 11 to 480p after it
surprised the market by announcing that it had sold two subsidiaries,
Holland &amp; Barrett and Kingswood, to Lloyds Chemists for Pounds 55m. Analysts
said the deal would reduce Booker's gearing by 20 points to 85 per cent. Mr
Carl Short of Nomura increased his next year's Booker forecast by Pounds 1m
to Pounds 114m, welcoming the news as 'a good deal for Booker'. Lloyds rose
3 to 278p on the announcement, but a Pounds 71.1m rights issue prevented a
larger advance.
Food specialists said Booker may announce a further small disposal this
morning to Albert Fisher. Fisher eased a penny to 120p ahead of its interim
results today. Profits of Pounds 44m against Pounds 19.9m last time are
expected.
First-quarter new business figures from Legal &amp; General were described as
disappointing by the market and the shares, additionally unsettled by a UBS
Philips &amp; Drew review of the life sector, fell 6 to 459p.
Maxwell Communication Corporation (MCC) added 6 at 236p in response to the
publication of the prospectus for the flotation of Mirror Group Newspapers
(MGN). MCC and MGN are both controlled by Mr Robert Maxwell.
A newspaper report revived talk that MB-Caradon, the building products and
printing group, was on the verge of selling its 25 per cent stake in CMB
Packaging. Mr Richard Rae at Hoare Govett said that the talked-of price of
Pounds 300m was in line with expectations and would give Caradon Pounds 100m
net cash. Caradon gained 12 to 234p.
Bid speculation took hold in Caird, the waste management company, and the
shares rose 7 more to 72p. Severn Trent Water is a major shareholder after
allowing its offer to lapse last December and must agree terms with Caird
before it can return within the statutory 12 months required by Takeover
Panel rules. Several main board directors of Caird announced further share
purchases on Tuesday.
Specialist engineer EIS Group rose to a 1991 high of 330p, up 8 1/2 , on the
good results and a positive statement which outweighed the call for fresh
funds of Pounds 18.3m. A sixfold increase in annual profits and an
encouraging view on current trading lifted Copymore 7 to 40p.
BAA added 16 to 444p following comments by Sir Norman Payne, the chairman,
that airline passenger traffic is almost back to pre-Gulf war levels. A B
Ports was up a penny at 267p despite late news the Monopolies and Mergers
Commission is to investigate cross-Solent ferry services. A B Ports'
subsidiary, Red Funnel, has a 20 per cent share in the market.
USM-quoted Radio City jumped 42 to 301p, after peaking at 318p, as it
revealed it was in talks that might lead to a bid. Traders suggested the
buyer was unlikely to be another radio company, given that the sector's
advertising revenue has been hard hit by the recession.
Two quoted holiday tour operators continued to be squeezed higher in
response to reports of record levels of bookings. Airtours rose 14 to 402p
and Owners Abroad firmed 6 to 92p.
Ivory &amp; Sime, the Edinburgh-based fund management group, bounced 8 to 123p
as investors scented increased business from the acquisition of fellow fund
group Argosy Asset Management. The latter had been facing uncertainty since
it lost management of the Merchant Navy Officers' Pension Fund last month.
Support of investment trust Berry Starquest also increased. Dealers became
wary, having seen buying recently from brokers not normally associated with
investment in the sector, and speculation arose of Berry perhaps reporting
some other development with the annual results, due tomorrow. The shares
rose 5 to 141p.
