<HEADLINE>
FT  18 APR 91 / International Company News: Higher nickel prices fail to
prevent Inco decline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HIGHER nickel prices raised operating earnings from primary metals at Inco
of Canada, the largest nickel company in the world, to USDollars 136m in the
first quarter from USDollars 110m a year earlier.
But overall net profit dipped 21 per cent to USDollars 53.6m or 50 cents a
share from USDollars 67.7m or 64 cents a year earlier because of lower
results from the alloys and engineered products business, currency
adjustments and higher taxes.
Revenues were USDollars 845m, against USDollars 735m.
Realised nickel prices averaged USDollars 3.94 a lb in the first quarter, up
from USDollars 3.69 a year earlier and USDollars 4.31 in the fourth quarter
of 1990. Copper prices were stable. Finished nickel inventory at March 31
was 54m lbs, down from 56m lbs at December 31 1990.
First-quarter nickel deliveries were 136m lbs against 123m lbs a year
earlier. Copper, platinum,silver and gold deliveries were all up
significantly, but cobalt declined.
Inco said the market value of 62 per cent-owned Consolidated TVX Mining was
almost USDollars 270m as of March 31, based on its gold mines in Quebec,
Brazil and Chile.
</TEXT>
