The company, which cautioned in December that it would produce a 'small' net
profit in 1990, is to omit the cash dividend, which in 1989 totalled Fl
3.60. Shareholders will receive a tax-free payout in shares of 2 per cent.
Turnover rose by 7.4 per cent to Fl 2.9bn, while pre-tax operating profit
tumbled to Fl 17.2m from Fl 60.2m.
In Rotterdam, the group's transport division was hit by a downturn at its 44
per cent-owned Europe Combined Terminals, the world's largest container
handling company. Unfavourable economic conditions in Australia and New
Zealand hurt the results of Internatio's trading division. At the same time,
its engineering division had had to create provisions for several technical
installation projects.
Internatio, which said it was unable to make a forecast for 1991 results,
plans to concentrate increasingly on its engineering and trading businesses
in future.
Nationale-Nederlanden, the biggest insurance company in the Netherlands,
said that losses at Orion, its UK subsidiary, were expected to narrow by
roughly one third in 1991, falling to around Pounds 30m (Dollars 53.7m) from
Pounds 48.8m in 1990.
Major losses at Orion, which had posted a profit of Pounds 6.3m in 1989,
were one of three main factors behind the 7 per cent decline in Nat-Ned's
1990 net profit to Fl 905m (Dollars 479m).
Nat-Ned's results were also affected by two severe winter storms which
lashed northwestern Europe in January and February 1990 and by the losses
posted by its non-life insurance activities in North America.
Mr Jaap van Rijn, Nat-Ned's chairman, said the North American non-life
insurance market was still in a down phase but should improve in 1992.
</TEXT>
