<HEADLINE>
FT  18 APR 91 / Teachers to have pay review body: Government's policy
reversal is dependent on unions agreeing to a no-strike deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN INDEPENDENT pay re-view body to assess teachers' pay and conditions is to
be set up later this year and could lead to a significant increase in salary
levels.
The setting up of the review body is conditional on teachers not resorting
to strike action.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the education secretary, who ann-ounced the sharp
reversal in policy to the Commons yesterday, expects the body to be in place
for next year's pay settlement.
The review body is intended to give teachers parity of treatment with
doctors, dentists, nurses and the armed forces, who have similar boards. The
Teachers' Pay and Conditions Bill, which would have restored negotiations
between teachers' unions and local authority employers, is to be withdrawn,
and a new bill will be introduced shortly.
The about-turn in policy signals the government's determination to enhance
the status of teachers as promised by Mr John Major during his campaign for
the Conservative party leadership last year.
Five of the six main teachers' unions gave broad support to Mr Clarke's
announcement. 'This is a step forward; we are very pleased indeed,' said Mr
Nigel de Gruchy, general secretary of the National Association of
Schoolmasters and Union of Women Teachers, the second largest of the unions.
The National Union of Teachers remained opposed. Mr Doug McAvoy, its general
secretary, said he 'totally rejected' the review body. 'It will be hidebound
to the government. And it will be the only pay review board which covers
conditions as well as pay,' he added.
School teachers' pay should be such as to 'recruit, retain and motivate'
high-calibre teachers, Mr Clarke said in his statement to the Commons.
He pledged that the government would implement the review body's
recommendations unless there were 'clear and compelling' reasons to the
contrary, but made its establishment conditional upon the teacher unions not
taking strike action on matters within its remit.
'My concern is that we should have a well-qualified and well-paid teaching
force . . . The body will not be subject to a pre-determined financial
constraint,' Mr Clarke said.
He also stressed the need for 'maximum flexibility' in teachers' pay to
reflect local labour-market conditions and good classroom performance.
Mr Jack Straw, Labour's ed-ucation spokesman, attacked the 'no strike'
condition, and condemned the proposed body as a 'breach of faith with the
teaching profession' but refrained from outright opposition.
