<HEADLINE>
FT  18 APR 91 / Parliament and Politics: Uncertainty on takeovers criticised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GREATER continuity between the Office of Fair Trading and the Monopolies and
Mergers Commission is needed to reduce uncertainty in industry over
government merger policy, the Commons trade and industry committee heard
yesterday, writes Robert Rice.
Mr Archie Norman, group finance director of Kingfisher, told the MPs'
inquiry into government policy on takeovers and mergers that the present
system had an unacceptable degree of uncertainty.
Any company contemplating a takeover needed a high degree of certainty
before embarking on an exercise involving substantial costs in management
resources and fees to advisers.
The OFT should be more candid with the parties on their reasons for
misgivings about a particular merger and should be prepared to identify
undertakings which which would satisfy them instead of waiting for the
parties to suggest them.
</TEXT>
