<HEADLINE>
FT  18 APR 91 / The Finance Bill: Revenue paves way for curbs - Pensions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Inland Revenue yesterday prepared the ground for the introduction of
investment restrictions on all small self-administered pension schemes. Such
schemes, much favoured by owner-managers of private businesses as a way of
reinvesting funds into their businesses, have so far escaped the investment
restrictions which are to be applied to other types of fund.
The Revenue has indicated several other restrictions it intends to
introduce. Loans from a pension scheme to a business will be limited to 25
per cent of the value of the fund in the first two years, and 50 per cent
after that. Also, there will be an effective ban on investment in
residential property.
The bill also contains a provision to amend UK pension regulations to take
account of the Barber v Guardian Royal Exchange ruling in the European Court
last May, which forces schemes to adopt a common pension age for men and
women.
Revenue rules had allowed full pension benefits to women who retired between
the ages of 55 and 70. In future, this will be limited to both women and men
retiring between the ages of 60 and 75. This will have little effect in
practice, since few occupational pension schemes recognise a retirement age
for women below the age of 60.
</TEXT>
