<HEADLINE>
FT  18 APR 91 / The Finance Bill: Drowning in a sea of paper - The need to
modernise the way tax law is made
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'The one certainty about our tax system is that what the government gives,
it must first take away. The archaic ritual by which parliament decides how
this shall be done is about as appropriate to a modern industrial democracy
as tally sticks to the international money market. We need radical reform of
our machinery for tax legislation. Only then will the legislation itself
become intelligent and intelligible. As long as we continue to worship in
accordance with established rites at the altar of the annual Finance Bill,
so long will our laws be confused and confusing.'
Sir Geoffrey Howe made this rousing call for reform in January 1977. A
couple of years later he was back in office and chancellor of the exchequer,
a post he held from 1979 to 1983. Once established in Number 11 Downing
Street he took no action to restructure the process by which tax law is made
in the UK. Nor, despite sporadic reforms of the tax system, has any of his
successors.
As a result, the tax system is less intelligent and intelligible than it was
in the late 1970s. Even professional tax consultants, who profit from the
obscurity of the law, admit to being exasperated at the complexity of the
UK's tax legislation.
They also complain about the volume of it: 3,338 pages of new law enacted
between 1975 and 1989. Some taxes were abolished during the course of the
Thatcher administration - for example Capital Transfer Tax - but this was
more than compensated for by a succession of voluminous Finance Acts.
'But for the efficiency of the tax publishing firms in producing materials
that annually update the tax legislation, the majority of tax practitioners
would not even begin to cope with the recent volume of legislation,'
reflects Malcolm Gammie, a tax partner in Linklaters &amp; Paines, in a
discussion document on tax reform first published last year and to be
re-issued later this year.*
Every tax partner has his or her favourite complaint about the tax system.
Adam Broke, formerly head of tax at Ernst &amp; Young, wishes that the Inland
Revenue would stop trying to make distinctions between income and capital.
Andrew Jones, Broke's successor at Ernst &amp; Young, objects to the arbitrary
pigeon-holing of different types of income. Mr Gammie notes that basic tax
concepts such as 'income', 'trade' or 'disposal', are not defined.
All are agreed that one central cause of the complexity is the way in which
tax legislation is enacted by means of the Finance Bill, the 'archaic
ritual' identified by Sir Geoffrey in 1977. The process works as follows:
proposals are worked up in great secrecy and announced in broad terms in the
Budget; about a month later a Finance Bill is published containing the
detailed legislation. This is debated in committee at the House of Commons
and enacted in the summer.
'Through the Finance Bill process, parliament performs the important
constitutional role of allowing the opposition to oppose what government
proposes,' says Mr Gammie in his discussion paper. 'It is, however, largely
ineffective as a body designed to scrutinise the detail of new legislation .
. . Measures which are inherently complicated or require the active
involvement of taxpayers to be implemented successfully, require more
detailed examination than the current Budget and Finance Bill process
allows.'
As Sir Geoffrey put it: 'There now follows the by-now-traditional struggle
on the Finance Bill Standing Committee. Both sides arrange themselves in
adversary relationship, with the opposition attacking the Treasury and the
Treasury defending . . . . The minister often feels no compunction about
glossing over questions which are beyond him, and the government
backbenchers often require little more assurance on a moot point than a
promise which trips lightly off the financial secretary's tongue 'to look at
the matter again.''
'Technical material is thus enacted through a parliamentary process where
the politicians are not interested in anything but knockabout point
scoring,' says Roger White, head of tax at KPMG Peat Marwick McLintock.
'Let's face it, there is no political will to get a better tax system. There
are no votes in it.'
Another problem is that MPs have no opportunity to influence tax policy:
pre-Budget secrecy ensures that there is, in most cases, no consultation
over tax proposals. MPs are up against a tight timetable and there are no
independent parliamentary experts to help them with the details. The only
advice comes from people outside parliament who have axes to grind.
Personal Equity Plans (Peps) were first introduced in the 1986 budget, Mr
Gammie says, without the benefit of a formal consultation process. Peps were
substantially modified in the 1989 budget, reflecting 'a failure to achieve
the objectives of the original proposal'. This is but one example of tax law
which has had to be rewritten in the light of experience. In more complex
areas, tax advisers are forced to rely on the Revenue adopting a pragmatic
approach to enforcement. A huge volume of case law has sprung up to give
interpretation on difficult points.
Mr Jones at Ernst &amp; Young says that, in an ideal world, tax law would be
codified and amendments would be made by inserting a new paragraph or
schedule into the relevant section of the code, rather than by a reference
in one Finance Act to a previous Finance Act.
Echoing some of Mr Gammie's conclusions, Mr White makes three proposals for
reform. First, he argues that the Revenue should consult more widely and
more frequently. Second, he believes that the Budget proposals should be
split into two pieces of legislation, one covering tax rates and allowances
and the other containing the detailed tax proposals (the technical bill
would not have to be enacted until October). Third, he believes there should
be a formal tax advisory committee - consisting of lawyers, accountants and
industrialists - which could debate the Revenue's proposals before they are
published in the form of a bill.
The Revenue is getting keener on consultation: last month it published
consultative documents on, among other issues, UK trusts, the taxation of
foreign exchange gains and losses and the taxation of subcontractors.
But other reforms are unlikely. The way tax is implemented now may be
tiresome to specialists but it is convenient for the government: huge pieces
of legislation can be ushered on to the statute book speedily and with the
minimum of fuss. The arcane ritual looks set to continue for some time.
*The Process of Tax Reform in the United Kingdom; published by the Law
Society of England &amp; Wales.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
