<HEADLINE>
FT  18 APR 91 / Public-sector deficit exceeds expectations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT recorded a deficit on its public-sector finances last month
of Pounds 3.1bn, the highest for three years.
The figure, released yesterday, illustrates the deterioration in
public-sector finances in recent months, largely as a result of the
recession.
It underlines fears in the City that the government's forecast Pounds 8bn
deficit in 1991-92 may be over-optimistic. Some economists believe the
deficit will turn out as high as Pounds 12bn.
The deficit for March, the last month of the 1990-91 financial year, was
roughly Pounds 600m higher than anticipated in the City.
It was caused mainly by a surge in local-authority borrowing and lower tax
revenues than expected. Borrowing by local authorities was Pounds 1.4bn last
month against Pounds 118m in February and Pounds 901m in March 1990.
Total local-authority borrowing for 1990-91 came to Pounds 3.5bn, more than
for the four previous years combined. Councils have been forced to borrow
more, largely as a result of difficulties arising from the poll tax.
Tax collected by the Inland Revenue in March amounted to Pounds 5.3bn,
against Pounds 5.7bn in February.
Growth in total tax contributions is likely to fall off over the next year
as a result of slower growth in incomes and a fall in company profits.
For the whole of 1990-91, the government showed a surplus on its
public-sector finances of Pounds 400m, as against a surplus in 1989-90 of
Pounds 7.9bn. In last month's Budget, the Treasury forecast a surplus for
1990-91 of Pounds 800m.
The projected deficit in the current financial year will be the first since
1986-87.
Net spending by government departments in 1990-91 came to Pounds 181.4bn, 16
per cent up on the previous year. Much of the extra spending was due to
bigger outlays on social security payments.
Privatisation proceeds for 1990-91 amounted to Pounds 5.3bn, of which Pounds
1.6bn were received in March, mainly from the first instalment of the sale
of PowerGen and National Power, the electricity generators.
Lex, Page 24
</TEXT>
