<HEADLINE>
FT  18 APR 91 / MMC to investigate Isle of Wight ferries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FERRY SERVICES between the mainland and the Isle of Wight are to be
investigated by the Monopolies and Mergers Commission, the government
announced yesterday.
The Office of Fair Trading said it had received complaints over a long
period about the prices charged by cross-Solent ferry operators.
Islanders on the Isle of Wight are wholly dependent on ferry services which,
they claim, are among the world's most expensive in relation to the length
of the crossing.
The biggest operator in the market is Wightlink, part of the Sea Containers
group, which operates three car ferries between Lymington and Yarmouth, two
passenger-only catamarans between Portsmouth and Ryde, and three car ferries
between Portsmouth and Fishbourne.
Wightlink's main competitor is Southampton-based Red Funnel Ferries, which
operates three car ferries and four car-carrying hydrofoils between
Southampton and Cowes.
The only other operator is Hovertravel, based on the Isle of Wight, which
runs two passenger-only hovercraft between Portsmouth and Ryde. Wight-link
yesterday quoted Pounds 22 to take a Ford Fiesta and two adults one way
across the Solent. Red Funnel Ferries quoted Pounds 23.20 for
Southampton-Cowes on a car ferry.
The Office of Fair Trading said its main concern was the dominant position
of the ferry operators in a market where there appeared to be limited scope
for new entrants.
Sir Gordon Borrie, the OFT's director general, said: 'I am not convinced
that there are no barriers to other entrants to the market and I have
received complaints over a long period.
'The companies do have a dominant position, and regular travellers between
the Isle of Wight and the mainland are almost totally dependent on ferries.
'I have therefore concluded that the issues can be resolved only through an
investigation by the MMC.'
The commission has until December 17 to report.
</TEXT>
