FT  18 APR 91 / Brazil tries to boost standing abroad
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINA LAMB
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRASLIA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Brazilian government is to launch a campaign to improve its
international standing, after last week's agreement with foreign bank
creditors on arrears payments.
'We feel we've turned a corner with this accord and can now hope for a new
climate in our international dealings,' said Mr Marcos Azambuja,
director-general of the Brazilian foreign office.
Ms Zelia Cardoso, Brazil's finance minister, is planning trips to Japan,
Europe and the US to try to recapture the support initially given to the
government's adjustment plan. President Fernando Collor plays host to
Britain's Prince Charles next week and, in June, will visit President George
Bush.
Brazil intends to remove the major thorns in trade relations with the US by
introducing patent protection and ending a law which prevents importing of
information technology similar to products manufactured in Brazil.
Brazil is blacklisted by the US commerce department for failing to deal with
these matters and for pirating of US films. The US, Brazil's biggest
creditor, did much to ensure the recent delay of a Dollars 350m loan from
the IADB. This loan may be released soon, following the arrears accord, but
Brazil is far from shedding its image in the international financial
community as the black sheep of Latin America.
