<HEADLINE>
FT  18 APR 91 / US troops survey sites in Iraq for Kurdish havens
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE, RALPH ATKINS, IAN DAVIDSON and TONY WALKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, LONDON, PARIS, CAIRO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US TROOPS yesterday moved into northern Iraq to begin surveying sites for
six or seven refugee centres for Iraqi Kurds under the protection of US,
British and French forces.
Initial Pentagon plans envisage between 5,000 and 10,000 US soldiers
building, running and guarding the camps.
Protection against possible Iraqi attack will be provided mostly by 'quick
reaction forces' of army and marine units based outside Iraq, probably in
Turkey, and mainly US combat air patrols.
Britain is expected to send about 2,000 troops. The UK 1st Battalion, the
Cheshire Regiment, was last night on standby. France is to supply about
1,000 troops.
Mr Pete Williams, Pentagon spokesman, said it would be two weeks before the
camps were 'ready to go'. He added that the refugees would probably be
disarmed to prevent the camps becoming bases for Kurdish rebels.
Iraq denounced the move as a continuation of unwarranted foreign
intervention in its affairs. It said it would hamper what Mr Ahmed Hussein
Khudayer, foreign minister, described as Baghdad's own efforts to resolve
the refugee problem.
A ceremony at which United Nations and Iraqi officials would have signed an
agreement on a plan for UN relief camps was abruptly cancelled at Iraq's
request.
An Information Ministry official said it 'needed to study further' some
parts of the plan, which would establish 'humanitarian centres' operated by
civilian UN personnel in northern and southern Iraq.
In Luxembourg European Community foreign ministers last night backed US
insistence that the return to Iraq was justified under the UN's resolution
688.
But the Anglo-US-French move took senior UN officials off guard. Ambassador
Eric Suy, who heads a UN team visiting Iraq to discuss the refugee crisis,
described the allied plan as 'absolutely a new element in the light of which
we will have to reconsider our position'. Mr Javier Perez de Cuellar, UN
Secretary General, said in Paris that the western plan to deploy troops in
northern Iraq would require Baghdad's permission.
'We would like first to be in contact with the Iraqi authorities, to see
what would be their reaction to such a military presence on their
territory,' he said.
Mr Perez de Cuellar said that, if the troops were to be deployed under the
aegis of the UN, 'it would be necessary to obtain the agreement of the
Security Council'.
Britain stressed its desire for the work of allied troops to be transferred
to the UN as soon as possible. Downing Street indicated it would support
another UN resolution to that effect if necessary.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, said his motive had been to take action
as swiftly as possible. 'We do not have a long time to leave the Kurds where
they are at the moment,' he said.
The prime minister received support from opposition parties for his
persistence in pushing his plan for havens.
Long-term need, page 4
Iraq's embrace, page 4
Oil ban plea, page 4
Parliament, page 14
Editorial Comment, page 22
