<HEADLINE>
FT  18 APR 91 / Money Markets: London rates ease
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
INTEREST RATES had a slightly softer tone in London yesterday, with news of
a bigger than expected March UK public sector borrowing requirement of
Pounds 3.1bn having little impact. A further decline in bank base rates is
expected,but not in the immediate future.
June short sterling futures continued to discount a cash three-month
interbank rate of slightly less than 11 1/2 per cent at delivery. In quiet
trading on Liffe the contract opened a little higher at 88.68 and finished
at 88.67 compared with 88.66 previously.
On the cash market three-month interbank eased to 11 7/8 -11 3/4 from 11
29/32 -11 27/32 per cent, while 12-month money fell to 11 3/8 -11 1/4 from
11 1/2 -11 3/8 per cent.
The Bank of England initially forecast a money market credit shortage of
Pounds 250m, but revised this to Pounds 350m at noon.
The authorities did not operate in the market until the afternoon, when help
was given via the purchase of Pounds 307m bank bills in band 2 at 11 13/16
per cent.
Bills maturing in official hands, repayment of late assistance and a take-up
of Treasury bills drained Pounds 145m, with a rise in the note circulation
absorbing Pounds 75m and bank balances below target Pounds 105m. These
outweighed exchequer transactions adding Pounds 75m to liquidity.
In Frankfurt call money eased to 8.80 from 8.85 per cent after the
Bundesbank added a net DM800m at this week's securities repurchase agreement
tender. The central bank accepted bids totalling DM25.9bn at a two-tranche
tender, offsetting expiring pacts of DM25.1bn. It provided DM16.8bn of
DM28-day funds at a fixed rate of 8.60 per cent and DM9.1bn of 63-day money
at variable bid rates, mostly 8.90 per cent.
Tax payments will keep credit conditions tight in the immediate future, but
this will be partly offset by redemptions and interest payments on
government paper.
The Bundesbank does not plan to hold a press conference after today's
regular council meeting, and sentiment in Frankfurt suggested that a rise in
official interest rates is unlikely, despite the recent speculation.
Credit policy was tightened a notch with a rise in the fixed rate at last
week's securities repurchase agreement, but there has been no similar move
this week.
</TEXT>
