<HEADLINE>
FT  18 APR 91 / International Capital Markets: Swedish firm packages two
junk bond deals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SWEDISH investment management firm, Carlson Investment Management, has
completed two deals backed by portfolios of junk bonds and placed with US
insurance companies. Further deals, to be placed with European investors,
are planned.
The US high-yield or junk bonds were repackaged to create two issues of
collateralised bond obligations (CBO). The first, a Dollars 115m CBO, will
be managed by Saudi International Bank. About Dollars 85m of senior bonds
were placed with US investors, while Dollars 10m of lower-ranked bonds were
bought by Saudi. Carlson will hold the remaining equity.
The portfolio yields around 15 per cent, while the new bonds pay interest of
just over 10 per cent, providing a substantial cushion for defaults.
Although economic recession in the US has increased the level of corporate
defaults, many investors now take the view that the worst is over, and are
becoming hungry for yield, said Mr Bjorn Carlson, the president of Carlson
Investment Management.
The second deal was a Dollars 225m package arranged in conjunction with
Massachusetts Mutual Life. An issue of Dollars 180m bonds was placed with US
insurance companies, with the two arrangers holding the equity. Both issues
were rated Double-A2 by Moody's and have an expected life of about eight
years.
</TEXT>
