<HEADLINE>
FT  18 APR 91 / International Capital Markets: Japanese railway in straight
issue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
KINKI Nippon Railway, a leading Japanese private railway company, launched
the first straight bond issue by an industrial company for two years
yesterday, writes Emiko Terazono in Tokyo. The nine-year bonds are worth
Y10bn with a coupon of 7 per cent.
This will be the first domestic straight bond issue by a industrial company
since Mitsubishi Estate's flotation in November 1988, only a month after the
market was opened to industrial companies.
Japanese companies have since relied on equity-linked funding, such as
warrant bonds and convertible bonds, and kept their distance from the
straight bonds.
Government restrictions preventing companies with low ratings from financing
had partly stemmed the flow, as had the high commission costs, which had
made the bonds less attractive than equity-linked issues.
The result has been that only a select group of utilities companies, such as
electrical power companies and Nippon Telegraph and Telephone, have used
straight bonds.
But tighter lending policies enforced by Japanese banks and a realisation of
the risks linked to equity financing in a volatile stock market have
prompted companies to seek other sources of financing.
Leading industrial companies are expected to turn to the straight bond
market. Mitsubishi Estate has again filed applications with the Ministry of
Finance, and plans to issue a total of Y200bn within the next two years.
Mr Mitsuru Nagai, director and general manager at Kinki Nippon Railway's
finance and accounting division, said that the sluggish stock market has
made the company cautious about equity linked financing.
'And you can't get a bank to lend Y10bn on the spot these days,' he added.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
