<HEADLINE>
FT  18 APR 91 / International Company News: American Airlines posts Dollars
195.6m loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AMERICAN Airlines, one of the two biggest US carriers, yesterday kicked off
a dismal quarterly reporting season for the US airline industry by
announcing that it lost Dollars 195.6m in the first three months of the
year.
The figures bear the full brunt of the traffic slump, which resulted from
the Gulf War and the deepening domestic recession.
In addition, Mr Bob Crandall, American's forthright chairman, pointed to the
uncertainty created by difficult labour negotiations. The airline also
suffered from the loss of around 450 pilots called up to serve in Operation
Desert Storm.
'The net effect was to make our first quarter uniquely unhappy,' he said.
Wall Street, however, was braced for red ink, and American itself had
already warned of a significant first-quarter loss. Analysts were predicting
a loss per share of around Dollars 3, with the actual figure of Dollars 2.96
falling closely in line with expectations. Shares in AMR, the parent
company, gained Dollars 1 1/8 at Dollars 61 1/8 at midday.
American's hefty first-quarter loss compares with a Dollars 19.3m deficit in
the first three months of 1990, and a Dollars 215.1m deficit in the
October-December quarter. The first quarter of any year is traditionally a
weak period for the airline industry, although in 1989 and 1988 American did
make significant profits during the first three months.
AMR's revenues during the first quarter of 1991 rose marginally, from
Dollars 2.69bn to Dollars 2.77bn, but there was a significantly sharper
increase in operating costs, up by 11.6 per cent at Dollars 3.01bn. Labour
costs rose by 12.3 per cent, while fuel expenses were 11.1 per cent higher
than in the previous year, at Dollars 476.4m.
Capacity, in terms of available seat miles, increased by 2.5 per cent
year-on-year, but the passenger load factor fell from 59.9 per cent to 56.5
per cent. American said that the break-even load factor for the first
quarter was 63.5 per cent, up from 60.6 per cent a year earlier.
However, Mr Crandall struck a brighter note over future prospects. 'Fuel
prices have declined,' he said, 'and we anticipate lower costs for the
remainder of the year.' Sales, he added, had been picking up recently and he
suggested that there was 'some evidence' that the economy is strengthening.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 29
</PAGE>
