<HEADLINE>
FT  18 APR 91 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
By the age of 13 most of us had forgotten those joke questions like 'Please
sir, do you mean the natives were revolting?' But they were all remembered
by Talbot Rothwell who went on to write the scripts for most of the Carry On
films. If you are one of those rare people who have never seen one, you can
judge the general standard by watching Carry On Up The Khyber (6.00 BBC2),
remembering that this is among the better ones.
Sadly it looks as though television's tendency to turn moderately personable
presenters into hysterical show-offs is beginning to affect Keith Floyd. He
used to be a natural enthusiast, but in his new series about cookery in
Australia, Floyd On Oz (8.00 BBC2), he looks as though he has overdosed on
uppers.
Revelations about Chernobyl have been occurring virtually since the
explosion. The latest come from This Week (8.30 ITV) on how radioactive
debris was removed. Channel 4 repeats the 'controversial' documentary about
the killing of unarmed IRA terrorists in Gibraltar, Death On The Rock
(9.30).
