<HEADLINE>
FT  18 APR 91 / Parliament and Politics: Committee considers recalling
governor - Harrods Bank
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A COMMONS committee is considering provoking a constitutional row by
recalling the governor of the Bank of England to give evidence for a second
time on action being taken against Harrods bank.
The trade and industry committee has taken advice from legal counsel on
whether the Bank's governor, Mr Robin Leigh-Pemberton, was right earlier
this year to insist that banking confidentiality laws prevented him from
detailing what measures had been taken.
Several MPs on the cross-party committee are angry at what they see as a
defiance of their powers to summon witnesses to answer questions. The legal
advice is believed to support those who argue the powers of parliament
transcend banking law.
The committee will debate what action to take next week. Members could
decide Mr Leigh-Pemberton has already given as much information as could
reasonably be expected. However, some believe there is a point of principle
and a constitutional anomaly at stake.
The long-running controversy stems from the damning report by government
inspectors on the takeover by the Fayed brothers of the House of Fraser, of
which Harrods bank is a subsidiary.
Several senior Conservative MPs want the Fayed brothers to be removed from
control of Harrods bank to protect the interests of its depositors.
Reflecting that anxiety, Mr Kenneth Warren, Conservative chairman of the
committee, issued a strong challenge at the end of last year to Mr
Leigh-Pemberton to give evidence about Harrods bank, saying it was 'high
time' he responded to the committee's request to do so.
During a tense evidence-taking session in February, Mr Leigh-Pemberton
repeatedly refused to answer questions about Harrods bank or the Fayed
brothers.
He cited section 82 of the 1987 Banking Act which makes it a criminal
offence for anyone, including the Bank's governor, to disclose information
received under the act relating to the business or other affairs of any
person without their consent.
</TEXT>
